Title:
Process Injection Part III

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post continues a series on Windows process injection, focusing on implementing and understanding a specific injection workflow in practice.  
- It explains how to place attacker-controlled code into a remote process and trigger execution, emphasizing the Windows APIs and required access rights.  
- The write-up discusses common injection primitives (remote memory allocation, writing payload bytes, and starting execution via a new thread or equivalent mechanism) and the typical pitfalls around permissions, architecture (x86 vs x64), and stability.  
- It is primarily useful for red teamers, pentesters, and malware developers who need a clear, step-by-step view of classic user-mode injection.  
- It’s interesting because it ties together the end-to-end mechanics of injection and highlights the operational details that often determine whether an injector works reliably.

Technical Focus:
- Windows user-mode process injection workflow
- Remote memory allocation and payload staging
- Cross-process memory writing
- Remote thread creation / execution triggering
- Process/thread access rights and token/privilege considerations
- x86/x64 (WOW64) compatibility considerations

Use Cases:
- Building a basic Windows injector for lab testing
- Understanding how commodity malware performs classic injection
- Developing or validating EDR detections around injection API sequences
- Troubleshooting injection failures related to privileges or architecture mismatches

Keywords:
Windows, process injection, CreateRemoteThread, VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, OpenProcess, remote thread, shellcode, payload staging, access rights, PROCESS_ALL_ACCESS, WOW64, x86, x64, user-mode, memory allocation, code execution, API sequence, endpoint detection, EDR evasion